<subSubSection pageId="73" pageNumber="74" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="73.[151,1436,151,1042]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[203,339,874,899]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" reason="1">Comments.</emphasis>
The terminalia are most characteristic for this species—the spine on the surstylus is apical, curved and very elongate, and the mesophallus and distiphallus are thin, cylindrical and subequal in length. The distiphallus of the 
<typeStatus box="[260,358,946,970]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">holotype</typeStatus>
was largely destroyed during the original dissection, and as such, has not been reillustrated here. The figure provided is from the original publication (
<bibRefCitation author="Spencer, K. A." box="[751,911,983,1007]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" refId="ref92189" refString="Spencer, K. A. (1981) A revisionary study of the leaf-mining flies (Agromyzidae) of California. University of California, Division of Agricultural Sciences, Special Publication 3273, 489 pp." type="book" year="1981">Spencer 1981</bibRefCitation>
). The only other known male was dissected to find the phallus missing.
</paragraph>
